<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Transport Committee</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from Cumbria County Council Integrated Transport Team (TIC 106)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How do Government and local authorities identify demand for passenger transport in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">isolated communities (including rural and urban areas and island communities)?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Given the rural nature of the County and the hi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gh distances that people travel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to access services in the Key Service Centres</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cumbria County Council has difficulty in meeti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he travel needs of all its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">residents.  The County Council is required to allocate funding to provide home to school, special needs and transport for social care clients.  In addition there is support for bus services where these are not provided commercial</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ly and for community transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to provide options when conventional services are not available</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Following work that was done using the Accession model to identify areas where there was not good access to scheduled bus services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it was agreed that it would</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be helpful to define a level of service that could be sustained by the Council particularly with regard to meeting the needs of more remote communities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This review looked at 790 communities across the County and mapped the available transport provision,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> where essential services (eg doctors, schools) were si</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uated and where people needed to travel for various purposes.  The aim was to provide a transport network which took into account both bus and rail services (the County </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a good rail network).  This</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> led to the Council having agreed criteria for the support of scheduled bus services when they were not provided </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">commercially</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Over 90% of bus services in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cumbria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are provided commercially in the main by Stagecoach.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The criteria are still applied and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">take account of the likely sustainability of bus services where there a few people likely to travel.  In some cases where need is identified funding can sometimes be provided on a short term basis to determine whether there is a likelihood that a scheduled</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> bus services will be viable on a longer term basis.  Whilst it is recognised that there may be a need for continued support a value for money criteria is applied as any bus service supported by the County Council needs to have a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n agreed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ratio of fares col</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lected to cost.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The County Council is not aware how central government identifies demand for passenger transport.  They will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">however </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have information on numbers travelling on concessionary bus passes as regular reports are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provided by Cumbria County Counc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">il to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Department for Transport.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To what extend are the needs of different groups of passengers (e.g. people with disabilities, older people, young people) taken into account in determining the provision of public transport to isolated communities?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n determining the provision to more isolated communities the County Council has over many years developed a range of solutions.  Where scheduled bus services are unlikely to be sustainable even with considerable financial support the transport provision is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> primarily demand-responsive.  There is an extensive network of Voluntary Car Schemes which are coordinated locally by volunteer coordinators.  In order to supplement the provision of transport for volunteers the County Council provides the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Rural Wheels</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">service which utilises the down time of small commercial providers.  Any</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">one</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> over the age of 16 is eligible provided they do not have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a scheduled bus service.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Management information regarding this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">service assist</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the County Council in providing evidence re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">garding patterns of travel from isolated communities.   Transport can be tailored to accommodate differing passenger needs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">within the agreed framework </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">but passengers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are required</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to be as flexible as possible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> regarding travel times, and occasionally days o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f the week</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to ensure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> transport resource is utilised as efficiently as possible.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the main challenges associated with providing better and more consistent bus and rail services to isolated communities? How can these challenged be overcome?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e availability of funding to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provide additional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improvements to bus services is the largest challenge as there is not sufficient demand to either run or enhance services without subsidy.  De-regulation of the transport network has resulted in commercial op</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">erators selecting the most profitable routes which tend to be in the more urban or densely populated areas leaving isolated communities to look to the local authority to meet their transport needs.  In addition where additional housing has been built in ur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ban</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the nature of these developments do not always consider the needs of operators to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be able to serve the areas by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bus.  The County Council works where possible with District and Borough Councils as well as developers to encourage sustainable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> through the Travel Planning process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The County Council’s aim is to integrate transport services that are statutorily required and contracts packages of work to link Home to School or Adult Social Care transport with supported scheduled bus serv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ices. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Increasingly the travel needs in the county </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">become more diverse as people travel in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">many </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">different directions to work and services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rather than along the traditional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">routes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e employment in the nearest Key Service Centre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The County Council became responsible two years ago for administering the English National Concessionary Travel Scheme.  In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cumbria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> there is a high proportion of use by concessionaires of scheduled bus services.  On the commercial services on average aroun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d 38% of passengers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are concessionary.  O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n some routes many of these in rural areas the proportion is much higher.  The Council had challenges during the first year to provide adequate funding to reimburse bus operators.  Consequently a decision was taken </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to reduce the reimbursement rate paid to operators from 65% to 58%.  In response to this the main operator (Stagecoach) increased their bus fares to people who travel without conces</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sions.  Unfortunately this lead</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to a decrease in people using buses and pay</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing fares.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition there is a high proportion of tourist travel in Cumbria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> particularly in South Lakeland which adds </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">significant pressure to the budget</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Recently there has also been a reduction in the amount of BSOG that transport operators have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">been able to claim and the County Council has been advised by Stagecoach that the reduction in the amount of money available together with other factors including the increasing cost of fuel has made some bus services less viable.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Access to Health, both G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P and hospital appointments is becoming increasingly challenging.  This is due to a number of factors including the change in eligibility criteria for free patient transport, increased patient choice around where consultations can be made and increased ava</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ilability of appointment times early in the morning, later in the evening and at weekends.   Cumbria County Council continues to engage with “health” to try and address transport issues from a strategic perspective. Whilst there has been some success, this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> work has not been made any easier by the continued changes in Health </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">governance structures </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">through the transition </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from the PCT to Clinical Commissioning Groups.  The provision of transport for patients in Cumbria is currently the responsibility of North W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">est Ambulance Services on contract to the CCG’s.  The County Council has also tried to engage with NWAS to have a collaborative approach to providing transport without success.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How effectively do Community Transport services address the needs of passenger</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> in isolated communities? How could Community Transport be improved?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The County Council’s definition of Commun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ity Transport is not restricted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to Voluntary Social Cars and Community Minibus schemes run under either Section 22 or Section 19 Permits.  It als</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o includes demand-responsive transport provided by Commercial Transport Operators under the umbrella of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Rural Wheels Scheme.  The Rural Wheels scheme provides a flexible transport service which only receives financial support when it operates.  This is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cost effective from the Council’s perspective when compared with the relatively high cost of supporting bus services particularly in more remote rural areas where there are few people travelling.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The County Council is only able</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to support the statutory c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oncessionary travel scheme so concessions are only available on scheduled bus services.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The provision of Community Transport other than the Rural Wheels type services relies heavily on volunteers which are easier to recruit in some parts of the county tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n in others.   The volunteers are required</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to both drive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">coordinate requests within</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> schemes.  Experience has shown when community transport schemes have started to pay staff they have soon become unviable. The development of the Rural Wheels scheme acr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oss the County has meant that the Council facilitates/supports transport in all areas irrespective of the availability of volunteers.  The development and ongoing support of Community Transport requires both financial and staffing suppor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t to achieve the be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">st results.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In this respect the County Council works closely with communities to develop schemes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Further flexibility in the S19 permit legislation could improve community transport. Such transport schemes can presently only be used by members of the sch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eme and are not available to the “general public” which prevents use by tourists and visitors. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The County Council is developing a new community transport solution “Community Wheels” which will deliver demand-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">responsive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> transport using fully accessible comm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">unity minibuses in partnership with local communities.  The viability of such services could be increased if visitors were able to have some sort of temporary membership that would allow them to pay to use the service. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Opening out membership could increa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se the patronage and therefore viability of some type of community minibus schemes.   However, this could cause</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> tensions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with the small commercial provider taxi who would normally provide transport where scheduled bus services or other transport was not av</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ailable.  The County Council relies heavily on the availability of a large number of small operators to provide transport for children with special needs and social care clients.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent should passengers in isolated communities be expected to rel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">y on taxis and other demand-responsive transport services?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Where scheduled services are not available either commercially or the Council is unable to support these services taxis and demand-responsive transport services provide a flexible </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">solution which is likely to be more appropriate for the user if it is door-to-door.   The County Council’s view is that the issue is less likely to be around whether the service is a bus, taxi or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">minibus, it is more likely to be because people will have to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> pay for any alternative to scheduled bus services and also that users will need to pre-book the transport.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst there is an argument that these services are not comparable to scheduled bus services the Council is clear that there needs to be options </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for people to travel where these services are not financially sustainable.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This does enable all residents in Cumbria to travel for essential services however there are difficulties in providing transport for employment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the main challenges associ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ated with funding transport services in isolated commu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nities? How can these services </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">be made more affordable?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The need for ongoing revenue funding at a time when the County Council has a number of pressures in maintaining a range of services including transport, the Council had to take the decision three years ago to withdraw support for some 19 bus services.  The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se services required considerable subsidy to maintain and in some cases alternatives have been found.  The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">level </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of bus fares in parts of the County are an issue and this is largely due to the cost of providing services and the distances travelled.  In add</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ition this situation has not been improved by the availability of ENCTS as operators do not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">receive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> full fare reimbursed.  The County Council has in the region of 96,000 residents who have concessionary travel passes and in addition a number of tourists tr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">avelling in the County who are eligible for “free” transport.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The County has an ageing population and given the current policy to enable people remain in their own homes for as long as possible this will continue to add demand for transport services and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consequent financial pressure to transport budgets.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Services can be made more affordable through efficient planning and coordination of transport requests to make sure that people living in the same area travel at a similar time.  This should generate a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dditional income and reduce the net cost of transport. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A more affordable and efficient transport network could be developed through further integration of services.  This would require flexibility to allow some types of service to carry the “general publ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ic” for example, non-emergency patient transport being linked with social care transport or to improve access to the local GP. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Transport services could be means tested so that only those in receipt of certain benefits receive a subsidised transport servi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> This was formally approved by the County Council in 2006</span></p></body></html>